arch funders, ‘knowledge brokers’ and research users, and considers the challenges and consequences of incentivising and rewarding particular articulations of research impact. It draws on wide ranging qualitative data, combined with theories about the science-policy interplay and audit regimes to suggest ways to improve research impact.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2023) 0aResearchxEvaluationzGreat Britain. 0aResearchxEvaluation. 7aEDUCATION / Research.2bisacsh1 aBandola-Gill, Justyna, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aMeer, Nasar, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aWatermeyer, Richard, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBristol UP/Policy Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311119671840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781447339861423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781447339861/original  a978-3-11-119671-8  Bristol UP/Policy Press Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles